@node SBCL
@subsection PVS in SBCL
PVS 8 now has SBCL as its default Common Lisp.
@c The primary developers can no longer afford the Allegro license for
@c providing a runtime version.
This has several differences with previous Allegro versions. The main
difference is that the Allegro versions were case-sensitive, whereas SBCL
is not. This can possibly affect proofs, strategies, and loaded Lisp
files.

With pvs-strategies and Lisp files, the place that was most common was
with PVS ids, for example @code{(eq id 'abs)} should instead be
@code{(eq id '|abs|)}. Note that @code{eq} in this case could be replaced
with @code{string=}, which is useful if @code{id} could be a string or
symbol. If case doesn't matter, then use
@code{string-equal}.@footnote{These are functions of Common Lisp, not
specific to PVS.} For example, @code{(string= 'a "a")} returns @code{NIL},
since @code{'a} is the same as @code{'A}, but this is true for
@code{(string-equal 'a "a")}.

@node       VSCode-PVS Integration
@subsection VSCode-PVS Integration

@node       Prover Threads
@subsection Prover Threads

One of the most difficult parts of the previous XML-RPC implementation was
the support for prover sessions. When in a prover session, a few
non-prover commands are possible, but they need to interrupt the prover to
run. In the relatively simple Emacs interface this is not difficult, but
supporting VSCode-PVS got complicated.

For this and other reasons, we decided to allow proofs to be run in separate
threads. The API is rather simple; there are two basic functions:
@itemize @bullet
@item @code{prover-init}: takes a formula reference, starts a prover session
  on a new thread, and returns a unique prover id and the initial sequent.
@item @code{prover-step}: takes a prover id and a proof command,
  applies the command to the thread associated with the id, and returns the
  result.
@end itemize

The result of these functions consists of a number of fields:
@itemize @bullet
@item @code{id}: the proof session id
@item @code{proofstate}: the resulting sequent
@item @code{status}: one of @code{init}, @code{waiting}, @code{proved}, or @code{quit}
@item @code{commentary}:
all of the messages that are generated between the proof command and the
resulting sequent are collected here. This includes information such as
instantiations that are found, counterexamples from running the
@code{random-test} command, etc.
@item @code{command}: the proof command that was given that led to this sequent.
@item @code{error}:
this is optional, and indicates there was an error in executing the
command. Note that this is not a Websocket error, but an error within the
prover, for example, typecheck errors. In this case, the sequent will be
the same one, as if the command was @code{skip}.
@end itemize

Because each session is on a thread with a unique id, several sessions can
be run concurrently; they can even be run on the same formula, allowing
one to explore different possible proofs at the same time, without having
to undo/redo a given proof. PVS already has a notion of multiple proofs
associated with a given formula, we make use of this both in generating
the unique id, and at the end, if the proof is saved, it is saved with
that id.

Here is an example run in the SBCL version. Note that this does not involve Websocket, but is easily converted to JSON for that purpose.
@verbatim
* (prover-init "axiom_of_archimedes")
(("id" . "axiom_of_archimedes0")
 ("proofstate" . 
axiom_of_archimedes :  

  |-------
{1}   FORALL (x: real): EXISTS (i: int): x < i
)
 ("status" . "init")
 ("commentary" "axiom_of_archimedes0 started at 2022-06-30T14:32:11+8"
  "Installing rewrite rule sets.singleton_rew (all instances)"))
* (prover-step "axiom_of_archimedes0" "(skeep)")
(("id" . "axiom_of_archimedes0") ("command" . "(skeep)")
 ("proofstate" . 
axiom_of_archimedes :  

  |-------
{1}   EXISTS (i: int): x < i
)
 ("status" . "waiting")
 ("commentary"
  "Skolemizing and keeping names of the universal formula in (+ -),"
  "this simplifies to:"))
@end verbatim

@node User-defined PVS Images
@subsection User-defined images
One strong advantage with SBCL is that images can easily be
generated. This is also possible from PVS itself, e.g., after loading a
large library. The function @code{make-new-pvs-image} takes a name and
generates a new image from the current state of the system. This means if
you loaded some PVS libraries, or some Quicklisp packages, they would be
included in the resulting image. To access this image later, use the
@code{-image @emph{name}} option to PVS.

It is probably easy to invoke this function such that the resulting image
has errors, and almost impossible to protect against this. For example,
soon after adding the logging facility it turned out none of these images
would run because they tried to write to broken stream. This was easy to
fix in the logger by catching the error and reopening the stream, but
what happens if a proof is started

Probably the best way to use @code{make-new-pvs-image} is to start a fresh
PVS, load up whatever libraries, packages, etc., you want, and then
immediately create the new image.

