@node PVS and Machine Learning
@subsection PVS and Machine Learning
We have been actively exploring the combination of PVS with machine
learning. Some examples of how agents could be created are in the
@code{python/websocket-examples} subdirectory. Note that these are not
complete, but are useful in showing how to create agents for PVS.

@c @node PVS Log Files
@c @subsection PVS Log Files

@c PVS now has the option to save log files for an interactive PVS session as
@c well as separately for each interactive proof. Though the logs are
@c relatively small, and the proof logs won't save duplicates, This feature
@c is off by default.

@c Session logs are primarily useful if you work regularly with PVS, in
@c effect they track your interaction with PVS Lisp through either Emacs or
@c VSCode. Actual file contents or diffs are not included, so this is not
@c enough to recreate a session, more like a reminder of when and how PVS was
@c used in the past.

@c Proof logs are actually valuable data for machine learning. In past
@c projects we tried to learn from the NASA libraries, but these have the
@c problem that they don't reflect failed proof attempts. The proof logs
@c capture all the prover interaction, almost as if cut and pasted from the
@c Emacs buffer.

@c The logs are controlled by the special variables
@c @itemize @bullet
@c @item @code{*pvs-log-preference*} - can be one of @code{nil}, @code{t},
@c       @code{:session}, or @code{:proofs}. Defaults to @code{nil}
@c @item @code{*pvs-log-directory*} - defaults to @code{~/.pvslog}
@c @end itemize

@c Note that these can be set in @code{~/.pvs.lisp}.

@c The log files are not buffered, thus even if the PVS process is killed the
@c log files will still be written.

@c @subsubsection PVS Session logs

@c Sessions logs are saved if @code{*pvs-log-preference*} is @code{t} or
@c @code{:session}. The files are named
@c @code{pvs-@emph{yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm}.log}, with the date representing the
@c start of the session. The contents are basically the interactions
@c with the Lisp process, i.e., the API with Emacs or vscode-pvs. In
@c addition, any messages, buffers, etc. That are passed will be shown.

@c @subsubsection Proof logs

@c Proof logs are kept in the @code{proofs} subdirectory of the
@c @code{*pvs-log-directory*}. Each proof log has a name of the form
@c @code{@emph{thy-fmla-yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm}.log}, where the timestamp reflects
@c when the proof is started. However, proof logs are not kept if they match
@c an earlier file, thus interactively rerunning a proof will only generate
@c one file. The proof log contains essentially what you see when running in
@c Emacs. However, any breaks into Lisp, tracing, etc. are not part of it.
@c However, proof commands such as @code{undo} and @code{postpone} do show
@c up. This makes these files useful for machine learning, as they will
@c reflect different proof attempts.

@c @subsection Proof Label Addition

@c This is a minor one, though it can be very helpful. The proof label above
@c a sequent now has the parent rule displayed. Sometimes after a subgoal is
@c proved, or postpone or undo commands are given, It can be difficult to
@c recall where the resulting sequent came from. Ancestry gives this
@c information, but seems a bit much.

@node Use of Quicklisp/ASDF
@subsection ASDF and Quicklisp
@emph{ASDF} (Another System Definition Facility) is the @emph{make} for Common
Lisp, and @emph{Quicklisp} is the package manager. The @code{pvs.asd} file
uses ASDF to specify the files and dependencies that make up the Lisp
components of the PVS system. Although most of the PVS system is built
this way, it is called from the Makefile, which is better at things like
installing Yices and compiling Emacs files.

The Makefile also installs the @code{~/quicklisp/} directory, which is
where packages loaded with Quicklisp are kept.  Using Quicklisp, PVS 8.1
loads the Websocket package, along with several others:
@itemize @bullet
@item @code{clack}: web application environment
@item @code{hunchentoot}: web server
@item @code{lparallel}: parallel programming library
@item @code{cl-json}: JSON encoder/decoder library
@item @code{bable}: charset encoding/decoding library
@item @code{cffi}: Common Foreign Function Interface
@item @code{anaphora}: anaphoric macro collection
@end itemize

If you want to install further packages into PVS, go to
@url{https://www.quicklisp.org/beta/} for an overview of how to use it,
and @url{https://www.quicklisp.org/beta/UNOFFICIAL/docs/} for a summary of
available Quicklisp packages.

@node Docker
@subsection Docker
A @code{Dockerfile} is included; this is mostly useful on a Windows
machine as PVS has not yet been ported to Windows. Read the Dockerfile
itself for details.


@node    8.1 Incompatibilities
@section Incompatibilities

There are a few incompatibilities in PVS 8.1, largely due to moving to
SBCL, and there mostly related to the use of case-sensitivity in Allegro,
which SBCL doesn't support.

@subsection Use of symbols in proofs
Many proof commands allow symbols or strings (within double quotes) as
input for PVS terms, for example, @code{typepred}. Thus both
@code{typepred x} and @code{typepred "x"} are accepted. However, in SBCL,
the former is treated the same as @code{typepred X}, which will either
result in a typecheck error or produce the type predicates for the wrong
term. Unfortunately, this is almost impossible to catch in general, though
in some cases (e.g., the @code{lemma} and @command{expand} commands) the
prover will try to find other cases before giving an error. Much of the
work done to produce the NASA PVS library fork was in fixing these kinds
of problems. In general, you should always use strings instead of symbols
for PVS terms.

@subsection Use of symbols in Lisp code
The above also is a problem in Lisp code, usually related to
@code{pvs-strategies} files. In some places the system was looking for
occurrences of @code{abs}, but using the symbol directly. It's OK in
Common Lisp to use the symbol, but it should be surrounded with vertical
bars, e.g., @code{|abs|} in order to work in both Allegro and SBCL. Note
that Common Lisp has many forms of equality, and if you want to check
against a string or symbol in a case-insensitive way, you can use the
built-in function @code{string-equal}.

@subsection TCCs
As usual, there are some TCC differences, mostly due to improvements in
the use of judgements. This is generally better for new proofs, but often
breaks existing proofs. Over the NASA PVS library this was a small
percentage, but is worth keeping in mind in moving to PVS 8.1.

Some of the proofs in the NASA PVS library were broken because they
brought in a TCC as a lemma, and TCC renumbering caused problems. As a
general rule, any such TCC should be extracted to a lemma, which can be
used to prove the TCC and safely used in other proofs.
